in martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Pederton was born in 1390, in Poltimore, Devon, England, her father, John Pederton, was 42 and her mother, Cecily Turney, was 30. She married John Bamfield in 1404, in Poltimore, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 3 daughters. She died in 1418, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1390–1418":"1390–1418","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","1372–1460":"1372–1460","1401–Female":"1401–Surnud","1405–1474":"1405–1474","1414–Female":"1414–Surnud","1452–1552":"1452–1552","1348–Male":"1348–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1460":"1460","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","1414":"1414","1348":"1348","1401":"1401","1552":"1552","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1474":"1474","1418":"1418","1405":"1405","Poltimore, , Devonshire, England":"Poltimore, Devon, England","Poltimore, Devon, England":"Poltimore, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1390–1418":"1390–1418","1420–Female":"1420–Kuollut","1372–1460":"1372–1460","1401–Female":"1401–Kuollut","1405–1474":"1405–1474","1414–Female":"1414–Kuollut","1452–1552":"1452–1552","1348–Male":"1348–Kuollut","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","1460":"1460","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","1414":"1414","1348":"1348","1401":"1401","1552":"1552","1420":"1420","1452":"1452","1474":"1474","1418":"1418","1405":"1405","Poltimore, , Devonshire, England":"Poltimore, Devon, England"